WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.480
My name is Erika, I'm a Senior Data Engineer at the Urban Institute, and the Urban Institute

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:15.360
is a non-profit research organization that provides data and evidence to help advance

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:16.360
upward mobility and equity.

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:21.160
Today I'll be talking about a tool that my coworkers at the Urban Institute and I built

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:24.040
called the Education Data Portal.

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:28.080
Before I get started, I have a confession to make, which is that I am very much not

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:30.120
an education data expert.

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:32.599
In fact, I know very little about education data.

00:00:32.599 --> 00:00:37.240
Luckily, I'm not here today to talk about the ins and outs of iPads or Common Core data,

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:42.200
and instead what I'm here to talk about is how the Education Data Portal bridges the

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:45.840
gap between data availability and data accessibility.

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:50.080
Specifically, there are three questions that I want to answer today.

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:54.599
The first is what do we mean by this gap between data availability and accessibility?

00:00:54.599 --> 00:00:59.080
The second, how does the portal bridge this gap so effectively?

00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:03.400
And lastly, why does this matter?

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:08.000
So every year, a handful of government agencies do the hard and important work of collecting

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.680
detailed data on K-12 schools, school districts, and in colleges in the U.S.

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:17.720
The goal of the Education Data Portal is to put all of this data under a single roof by

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:23.199
providing a freely available one-stop shop for all of the major national data sets released

00:01:23.199 --> 00:01:26.519
by these agencies.

00:01:26.519 --> 00:01:30.199
In many cases, these agencies have been collecting this data for a couple of decades, and as

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:35.279
you can imagine, there have been lots of changes to data formats, file structures, classifications

00:01:35.279 --> 00:01:36.559
over the years.

00:01:36.559 --> 00:01:42.440
So our goal is to do the hard work of harmonizing that data, that way we can do that work and

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:48.120
offload that from researchers and data scientists and other folks trying to use that data.

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:52.360
When I say we, I really mean our army of research assistants who do that hard work.

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:55.320
So much kudos to them.

00:01:55.320 --> 00:02:00.959
Ultimately, we do this to make it easier for both technical and non-technical users to

00:02:00.959 --> 00:02:05.000
look at trends over time and combine data from these different sources and just to put

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:08.440
that data at their fingertips a little easier.

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:14.000
So this is a little bit abstract, so to provide an example, suppose I'm interested in answering

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.759
the question of how has tuition in my alma mater risen over the last couple decades in

00:02:18.759 --> 00:02:19.759
my case.

00:02:20.759 --> 00:02:26.520
So I went to a tiny little liberal arts college in Northfield, Minnesota called Carleton,

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:30.119
and like many other delightful little liberal arts colleges, I probably have a rough sense

00:02:30.119 --> 00:02:33.960
that tuition over the last couple of decades looks something like this.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:38.119
However, as I mentioned at the beginning, I work for the Irvin Institute, and we take

00:02:38.119 --> 00:02:43.080
data and evidence very seriously, so I'm not just going to use my priors here, and suppose

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:47.880
I want to really get into the data and try to reproduce this plot myself.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.279
So first, suppose I live in a world without the education data portal.

00:02:51.279 --> 00:02:55.479
I'm also going to be showing a live look at my pain levels as I go through the process

00:02:55.479 --> 00:02:59.160
of answering this question without the education data portal.

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:02.399
The very first thing I'd have to do is just figure out which agency is collecting this

00:03:02.399 --> 00:03:03.399
data.

00:03:03.399 --> 00:03:06.240
As I mentioned at the beginning, I'm not an education data expert, so I just have to do

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.639
some Googling, figure out which website to go to, get to that website.

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:15.440
Next, I'd have to read through the data documentation, assuming that website has data documentation

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:20.360
for me to read, to figure out what tables am I looking for, which variables.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:25.119
Maybe I'll type the keyword tuition into some kind of a query, and then get a couple hundred

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:28.759
or a couple thousand tables back to figure out just where is the data that I'm looking

00:03:28.759 --> 00:03:30.759
for on this website.

00:03:30.759 --> 00:03:35.199
Next, I'd have to download individual data files for each year.

00:03:35.199 --> 00:03:40.039
So I think for folks who are used to working with government data, agencies typically report

00:03:40.039 --> 00:03:45.960
data as CSV files, or depending on the programming language you're using, SAS or SATA files,

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:49.679
which can be great if you use those languages, but it also means that in my case, I'd have

00:03:49.679 --> 00:03:54.199
to download 20-some individual data files, which again, not the end of the world, a little

00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:56.759
bit annoying, but you move on.

00:03:56.759 --> 00:04:02.160
So next, I would load those files into the programming language of my choice.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:06.839
This is what I like to call the choose-your-own data mishap trauma, but I think you can think

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:09.039
of any number of things happening here.

00:04:09.039 --> 00:04:13.800
Maybe it's that in the late 90s, a variable definition changed, or maybe earlier on, there

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:17.279
were three different files for this data, but then turns out later there were two or

00:04:17.279 --> 00:04:19.839
later one.

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:24.920
Maybe there is a 99 value for tuition, and while I think it would be great if Carleton

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:30.239
tuition costs $99, that more likely means that it was a total row where missing data

00:04:30.239 --> 00:04:32.320
or some kind of encoding.

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:37.839
So at this point, you can either cry, or you can reread the data documentation, figure

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:42.880
out what you did wrong, figure out what you need to redo, update your code.

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:47.279
The very fun part of setting yourself a calendar reminder to a year from now, do the same thing,

00:04:47.279 --> 00:04:52.359
go to the government website, download that data file, and last but certainly not least,

00:04:52.359 --> 00:04:54.920
hope that nothing changes.

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:59.359
Hopefully I belabored the point that this process is really tedious, it's really error-prone,

00:04:59.359 --> 00:05:02.200
and simply not fun.

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:04.760
So enter the education data portal.

00:05:04.760 --> 00:05:07.880
Suppose you're an R user, like I think lots of folks in this room might be.

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:12.959
Great, we built an R package for you called education data, you can download it from CRAN,

00:05:12.959 --> 00:05:20.079
and with just a single call to the get education data function, you can get a plot that looks

00:05:20.079 --> 00:05:24.679
remarkably similar to what I had in my brain at the very beginning of this.

00:05:24.679 --> 00:05:29.839
Suppose you're not an R user, instead you're a Python user, great, we also built a package

00:05:29.839 --> 00:05:35.000
for you, less great is that's not yet publicly available, but it will be soon, but again,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.799
very, very similar syntax, very, very similar, and just being a little bit, a lot bit easier

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:43.799
to get this data.

00:05:43.799 --> 00:05:48.440
Suppose you are not an R or Python user, instead you're a Stata user, and I recognize I'm at

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:53.359
a conference evangelizing open source technology, and Stata is very much not an open source

00:05:53.359 --> 00:05:57.839
technology, but ultimately in the space I work in, I work with a lot of economists,

00:05:57.839 --> 00:06:03.480
I work with a lot of policy researchers, and again, you can see with just fewer lines

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:09.480
of code than the R and Python syntax, similar plots, prelabeled, which is great, so yeah,

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:14.720
again, just trying to make that data a little bit more accessible for them.

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:21.760
Suppose you, oh, gosh, suppose you are not a programmer, and instead you're someone who

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:32.480
maybe just wants to click a couple of buttons, toggle a couple of things, specify the states

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:35.880
or the time frame that you're interested in, and just get an Excel spreadsheet, so again,

00:06:35.880 --> 00:06:39.760
this is really looking at that non-technical user, someone who doesn't know R, doesn't

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:43.880
know Python, doesn't make sense for them to learn those languages, they just want to click

00:06:43.880 --> 00:06:47.679
a couple of buttons and get data as an Excel spreadsheet, great, we also built a tool for

00:06:47.679 --> 00:06:50.679
them, and that's what this looks like.

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:55.239
So hopefully I've made clear that I personally think the Education Data Portal does a really

00:06:55.239 --> 00:06:59.480
good job of bridging this gap between data availability, so that's the agency, or that's

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:03.640
the data that these agencies are publishing, and then data accessibility, so it's really

00:07:03.640 --> 00:07:08.720
putting that data at the fingertips of the R programmer, the Python programmer, the data

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:10.720
explorer user.

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:14.640
So the second thing I want to talk about today is how do I think the portal bridges this

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:15.640
gap so effectively?

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:20.480
Specifically, I think it's because it focuses on two things.

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:23.160
The underlying API, and then data documentation.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:27.119
I'll talk about these in more detail.

00:07:27.119 --> 00:07:30.920
So I think in contrast to these agencies, as I mentioned before, who typically publish

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:35.640
data as flat files, that's like CSV files or things like that, or in programming language

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:41.600
specific files, the Education Data Portal really has an API at its foundation, or a

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:44.720
language agnostic API at its foundation.

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:47.480
So this includes a couple of things.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:53.000
First it includes the actual data endpoints, that's around 110, 115, endpoints that actually

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:57.880
contain the data, so that's tuition data, that's finance data, that's the actual data

00:07:57.880 --> 00:08:00.279
that users use.

00:08:00.279 --> 00:08:05.640
It also includes about a dozen metadata endpoints, so these are API endpoints about the data,

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:13.959
so that's information like what years are available or what variables exist for an endpoint,

00:08:13.959 --> 00:08:18.600
or what values, like what are the special values for each of the variables.

00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:23.119
So there's a lot of reasons why focusing on the underlying API here is very helpful, but

00:08:23.119 --> 00:08:28.359
I think the main reason for us, and the main reason for us is just for a lot of these datasets,

00:08:28.359 --> 00:08:33.559
they're really big, just in terms of, I also realize that big is like very much of a spectrum,

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:38.440
but they're really big in terms of the, they're really big for the folks who are trying to

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:42.559
do the things that they're trying to do with this data, and I mean that both in terms of

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:46.919
the number of rows, and then also the number of columns, so I think it's pretty, it's not

00:08:46.919 --> 00:08:52.039
uncommon for rows to, for rows of data, if you think about, I don't know, disaggregated

00:08:52.039 --> 00:08:59.960
data by like race, ethnicity, sex, institution, then maybe also like the type of, like the

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:03.599
major or something like that, you can easily get into the tens or hundreds of millions

00:09:03.599 --> 00:09:08.559
of rows here, which again, for a lot of people, that really isn't big data, but for some people,

00:09:08.559 --> 00:09:12.960
for a lot of people, it's just more data than it's easy to work with in the conventional

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:17.880
languages they're used to work with, or conventional frameworks, so by virtually building an API,

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:22.679
you don't have to download that 10 million row CSV file, instead, if you're only interested

00:09:22.679 --> 00:09:28.119
in data from Carleton College, or from Minnesota, or for computer science majors, you can specify

00:09:28.119 --> 00:09:32.520
through query string parameters, exactly which rows do you need, through that filters, and

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:37.239
you just grab those from our database, without having to download the exact files, just make

00:09:37.239 --> 00:09:41.039
it a little bit easier for users to only get the data that they need, similarly, you

00:09:41.039 --> 00:09:45.039
can specify the columns you need, so if you only need tuition, you only need the name

00:09:45.039 --> 00:09:50.320
of the institution, you don't have to get all 100, 100 plus variables that a lot of

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:56.280
these agencies typically include in the data files that they start with, and the last thing

00:09:56.280 --> 00:10:00.000
that I think, personally and selfishly, is the best thing about having this focus be

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:05.359
on the underlying API, is that all of the other tools, packages, and documentation are

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:09.799
built directly from these endpoints, so what that means, is that I don't have to spend

00:10:09.799 --> 00:10:15.919
all day, every day, maintaining SATA packages, and R packages, and Tableau dashboards, and

00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:21.359
JavaScript sites, all I have to do, is really make sure that the API is fast, it's reliable,

00:10:21.359 --> 00:10:25.919
and that's accurate, and by virtue of having this single source of truth, I just freeze

00:10:25.919 --> 00:10:32.559
up a lot of my time, to not have to deal with all these other things that are going on,

00:10:32.559 --> 00:10:36.520
so the second thing that I think the education data portal does really well, that I think

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:44.200
really provides a major value-added over the existing data, is that it really treats data

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:49.599
documentation as a first-order feature, and a first-order value-add, and not as an afterthought,

00:10:49.599 --> 00:10:54.960
where I think data documentation, and documentation in general, tends to fall, so I was told that

00:10:54.960 --> 00:11:00.880
showing a slide with 1,400 variables wouldn't be very aesthetically pleasing, so instead

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:05.359
I'm going to focus on two things that I think really just provide a lot of value, the first

00:11:05.359 --> 00:11:10.000
is that data documentation really is written for both humans and machines, and for anyone

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.960
who's seen Johnny Bryan's great talk on naming things, I think a lot of the same principles

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:20.919
about thinking about who your end user is, whether that is a human or a machine, and

00:11:20.919 --> 00:11:24.000
think about making your work accessible to them, I think that also really applies to

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:30.479
documentation here, especially data documentation dictionaries, and the second thing is that

00:11:30.479 --> 00:11:34.640
the documentation really provides the user with details on demand, and this is borrowed

00:11:34.640 --> 00:11:41.119
from a design principle, and I'll talk about these in a little bit more detail now, so

00:11:41.119 --> 00:11:45.239
when I say data documentation is written for both humans and machines, here's an example

00:11:45.239 --> 00:11:51.400
of a variable, degree of urbanization, I as a human think this is written for me, like

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:56.880
I think I know what it's telling me, I have the relevant information, it's pretty user-friendly

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:03.960
for someone looking at it. Here's that same documentation, or data documentation, but

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:10.599
provided in a way that I think is machine-readable, so I'm making an API call to the API variables

00:12:10.599 --> 00:12:15.000
metadata endpoint that I mentioned earlier, you can get the exact same information, so

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:19.359
you get the label, you get the data type, and then you've got standardized formats of

00:12:19.359 --> 00:12:24.840
the values written in a way that's for machines. Since there are a couple of obvious advantages

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:29.200
of this, maybe you're someone who's trying to make hundreds of plots, and you want to

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:32.880
automate adding labels, or maybe you're someone who wants to add captions, you're building

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:36.760
a dashboard, I think there are many numbers of things that you can do that really get

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:42.000
a lot of value from having this data documentation be written, again, both for humans on the

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:48.679
left, and also in a way that can be programmatically accessed on the right. The second thing I

00:12:48.679 --> 00:12:52.799
want to talk about on the data documentation front is that it provides the user with details

00:12:52.799 --> 00:12:58.919
on demand. So here you can see that same variable by hovering over the tooltip, a little

00:12:58.919 --> 00:13:04.080
information tooltip, you can see that before 2005, there were nine types of urban-centric

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:08.559
locales, and after 2005, the variable switched, which, again, there are lots of folks for

00:13:08.559 --> 00:13:12.159
whom that's really important information for them, they really need to know that, which

00:13:12.159 --> 00:13:16.840
is great, but there's also lots of folks who that just isn't relevant information for them.

00:13:16.840 --> 00:13:21.679
So if this was something like a PDF, or an HTML table, if I'm someone who's just trying

00:13:21.679 --> 00:13:26.000
to quickly scan a page, figure out what table am I looking for, what variables am I looking

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:30.599
for, having all of this information just there for you really affects the user's ability

00:13:30.599 --> 00:13:36.559
to just quickly scan. So instead of providing users with this detail on demand as opposed

00:13:36.559 --> 00:13:42.159
to just there for you, I think it really provides a huge value add for making this a first-order

00:13:42.159 --> 00:13:49.679
feature and value add. So I think implicit within this focus on both the underlying API

00:13:49.679 --> 00:13:54.359
and the data documentation is that the Education Data Portal really is a collaboration of folks

00:13:54.359 --> 00:13:58.840
with really deep education expertise, so that's Erica, Jay, and Leo, as I mentioned on the

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:04.039
bottom, so these are folks who have been using this data for years, in some cases decades,

00:14:04.039 --> 00:14:10.520
who really know the ins and outs of when variables change, what that means in terms of implications,

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:13.719
and then it also means that it's a collaboration with folks like me who are on the technology

00:14:13.719 --> 00:14:18.799
side who, I couldn't tell you what the majority of acronyms mean, when I do, I usually get

00:14:18.799 --> 00:14:23.559
them wrong, but what I do know how to do is do things like make fast APIs or build

00:14:23.559 --> 00:14:28.239
dockerized applications, and more importantly, I also know how to work with the folks in

00:14:28.239 --> 00:14:32.840
the education team and vice versa, and I think by really having that mutual respect for what

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:40.760
we both bring to the table, I really think it just makes Spur a stronger and better tool.

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:45.159
So the last and final thing I want to talk about today is why bridging this gap matters,

00:14:45.159 --> 00:14:49.919
and ultimately, I think it matters because different people ask different questions.

00:14:49.919 --> 00:14:53.280
So now I get to do what I think is my favorite part of the job, which is talking to real

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:59.280
users and seeing what they're doing with data from the education data portal.

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:02.640
So the first example I want to talk about is an organization we've worked with called

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:06.960
Reboot Representation, and they're a nonprofit that's committed to increasing the number

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:13.880
of black, Latina, and tribal women who work in technology fields, so they've been using

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:18.239
the portal to answer questions like which colleges are graduating or which colleges

00:15:18.239 --> 00:15:23.239
have large numbers of women of color graduating with computer science degrees, which of these

00:15:23.239 --> 00:15:30.559
colleges are tribal colleges or HBCUs, and also how this is changing over time.

00:15:30.559 --> 00:15:34.200
I also recently found out that a friend of mine whose mom is a middle school principal

00:15:34.200 --> 00:15:38.679
in New Jersey had been using the portal to answer questions like how do student test

00:15:38.679 --> 00:15:43.599
scores in my school compare to other schools across the district, and how do they compare

00:15:43.599 --> 00:15:47.000
to other schools across the state?

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.599
Another question they found out she'd been answering with the portal lately is how has

00:15:49.599 --> 00:15:53.239
this changed over the course of the pandemic, which, again, I think that's a question a

00:15:53.239 --> 00:15:56.799
lot of teachers and a lot of administrators are thinking about, so having this data at

00:15:56.799 --> 00:16:00.479
her fingertips has been helpful for her.

00:16:00.479 --> 00:16:05.599
The last example I want to talk about is a particularly fun many layers of education

00:16:05.599 --> 00:16:10.320
example, but a colleague of mine was recently, a couple months ago, was picking up her kid

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:14.479
from school, and she was wearing an Urban Institute-branded fleece, and another parent

00:16:14.479 --> 00:16:17.679
came up to her and was like, oh, do you work at Urban?

00:16:17.679 --> 00:16:22.039
I actually work at PBS, and I don't know if you've heard, but Urban makes this great tool

00:16:22.039 --> 00:16:26.719
called the Education Data Portal, and we've been using it to pull geocoded lists of schools

00:16:26.719 --> 00:16:31.320
and school districts to think about how that maps to our broadcasting coverage, and I talked

00:16:31.359 --> 00:16:36.760
about ways to use data on school funding to specifically identify under-resourced schools

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:43.479
to think about how that maps to where PBS has prioritized their broadcast coverage.

00:16:43.479 --> 00:16:49.280
So these are just three of thousands of questions that users are answering at the portal, and

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:54.599
this graph is probably pretty tiny, but last month you can see 4,000 unique users, where

00:16:54.599 --> 00:17:00.679
here I'm using IP addresses as a proxy for users, because we don't collect that data,

00:17:00.679 --> 00:17:03.679
but what I think is interesting, or I think lots of things are interesting about this.

00:17:03.679 --> 00:17:07.599
One, I think, is just the fact that as much as I would love to believe that everyone is

00:17:07.599 --> 00:17:12.040
using the R package and everyone's using the Data Explorer, ultimately that's just a very

00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:16.099
small number of the folks who are using the portal every month, and the vast majority

00:17:16.099 --> 00:17:21.359
are coming from folks who are either directly connecting from the API, so that's using Python

00:17:21.359 --> 00:17:26.599
or JavaScript or other applications or other programming languages that we don't have packages

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:31.239
for, but what a lot of that also is is folks who are building their own Power BI or Tableau

00:17:31.239 --> 00:17:36.319
or whatever other kinds of dashboards or other kinds of user interfaces to build their own

00:17:36.319 --> 00:17:42.119
tools to help folks who they're one step closer to answer their own questions.

00:17:42.119 --> 00:17:46.199
So ultimately, while I think folks in this room who are data scientists or data engineers,

00:17:46.199 --> 00:17:50.040
it comes really natural to us to think about building tools for other data scientists or

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:54.599
other engineers, similarly as R programmers or Python programmers, it might be really

00:17:54.599 --> 00:17:59.640
natural to think about building tools for other R programmers and Python programmers,

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:04.680
but I think that by unlocking data for more people, we can allow more questions to find

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:10.640
evidence-based answers that ultimately drive impact in the places that folks are working.

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:11.640
Thanks so much.

00:18:11.640 --> 00:18:23.319
I also have a slightly unreasonable number of hex stickers, so if anybody would love

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:27.839
to not take back to D.C. with me, so if anyone's interested.

00:18:27.839 --> 00:18:28.839
Thank you so much, Erika.

00:18:28.839 --> 00:18:30.079
Give her a round of applause.

